    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">DISTRIBUTED DATA MINING CREDIT CARD FORGERY DETECTION</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Anandharaj R<br />Balaji T C<br />Bhaskar, Bijesh K</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">DISTRIBUTED DATA MINING<br />CREDIT CARD FORGERY DETECTION</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">1-May-2008 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">3972</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Credit card transactions continue to grow in number, taking a larger share of the US payment system, and have led to a higher rate of stolen account numbers and subsequent losses by banks. Hence, improved forgery detection has become essential to maintain the viability of the US payment system. Banks have been fielding early forgery warning systems for some years. We seek to improve upon the state-of-the-art in commercial practice via large scale data mining. Scalable techniques to analyze massive amounts of transaction data to compute efficient forgery detectors in a timely manner is an important problem, especially for e-commerce. Besides scalability and efficiency, the forgery detection task exhibits technical problems that include skewed distributions of training data and non-uniform cost per error, both of which have not been widely studied in the knowledge discovery and data mining community. In this article we survey and evaluate a number of techniques that we have proposed and implemented that address these three main issues concurrently. Our proposed methods of combining multiple learned forgery detectors under a &quot;cost model&quot; are general and demonstrably useful; our empirical results demonstrate that we can significantly reduce loss due to forgery through distributed datamining of forgery models.
Today, credit cards are the most common methodology used by all or most of the customers for shopping. The banking sector has made major significant changes, in several options. Out of these the most important parameter, is the introduction of credit cards.
There are lots of customers, who misuse the facility of credit cards, make lots of purchases and do not plan their purchases end up not paying up the credit card bills.The bills are not paid correctly and slowly there are lots of customers who ultimately stop paying, finally the bank is ending up with a lot of loss, resulting in lots of customers not paying any amount. Huge data sets are to be observed regarding the payment. This becomes the data mining. So in order to determine the number of customers involved in non â€“ payment of funds for credit card, which is one type of credit card forgery, there is the proposed system</td></tr>
